=== TASK ===
# Password Reset Page Development Prompt

## Overview
Build a secure, user-friendly Password Reset flow that supports requesting a reset email, token verification, and setting a new password with an integrated strength meter. The page must integrate with the LifeOps authentication system (email/password, social OAuth, SSO, JWT sessions, RBAC) and adhere to the project’s design system, accessibility, and runtime-safety standards. All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods, initialize arrays with useState([]), and follow the Supabase null-safety patterns described below.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
The Password Reset Page enables users to recover access to their account through a secure, auditable flow:

- Step 1: Request Reset Email
  - UI: Email input, email validation, CAPTCHA/Rate-limiting control, and a submit button.
  - Behavior: Submit triggers a reset-token email to the user if the address exists (without disclosing user existence to protect privacy). Server logs the request for auditing and rate limits per IP/user.
  - UI cues: Inline validation, disabled state while processing, success/failure messaging. Optional: show a progress illustration or status badge.

- Step 2: Token Verification (Magic Link or Token Entry)
  - Flow variants:
    - Magic Link: User receives an email with a one-time login link containing a short-lived token.
    - Manual Token Entry: If the system supports token entry, a token field accepts a one-time code.
  - UI: If using a magic link, a confirmation screen points users to their email. If token entry is used, an input for the token with a “Verify” button and a countdown/expiry indicator.
  - Behavior: Validate token server-side; on success, navigate to the New Password form. On failure, provide clear error messages and retry options.

- Step 3: Set New Password
  - UI: New password input, confirm password input, and a live password strength meter/indicator.
  - Validation: Enforce password policies (length, complexity, entropy requirements) and confirm password match.
  - Security: On success, create a new authenticated session (JWT or refresh token as per the app’s flow) and redirect to login or dashboard depending on RBAC and user state.
  - UX: Visual strength meter with color cues, actionable feedback for improvements, and a strong success message with a login link.

- Step 4: Confirmation & Next Steps
  - UI: Confirm reset completion, offer to log in, return to sign-up, or navigate to support. Include a rollback/audit trail link for admins (if appropriate).
  - Accessibility: All steps are keyboard-navigable, screen-reader friendly, and follow color-contrast standards.

- Security & Compliance
  - Rate limiting and CAPTCHA controls to prevent abuse.
  - No leakage of user existence; responses should mask whether an email is registered.
  - All operations are logged with a traceable artifact (run IDs, IP address when appropriate, timestamps, user agent).
  - RBAC considerations: Only users with appropriate roles can trigger certain password-reset flows in admin contexts.

- Connected Features
  - User Authentication: The page should tie into the LifeOps authentication module (email/password, social OAuth, SSO, JWT sessions, RBAC) and share consistent error messaging and session handling.

- API Integrations
  - No direct external APIs beyond the app’s own authentication service. All calls use the project’s standard API surface (REST or GraphQL) and adhere to the runtime-safety rules.

- Visual Guidance
  - The look-and-feel must align with the LifeOps UI: dark UI, elevated cards, dense information density for power users, with subtle depth and a reaction to interactions per the design system.

